arch:property.oc:show_val: Main construction of the Bath Complex.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

Locus 70 is the leveling course below the second paver from the east in the bottom row of the step of Locus 48 (the stairs at the west extent of the colonnaded corridor). The locus consists of small unhewn stones and surrounding soil, creating a level surface for the steps resting on top of it. The soil is a fine compacted silt/sand (Munsell 7.5 YR 5/4 brown). Hopefully some of the finds from this locus will help pinpoint the date of construction of this stairway. There are inclusions of pottery, bone, glass, and small stones. Part of the construction of the stairway, Locus 70 is phased to Stage 2, the main construction of the Bath Complex.
0.32 m north south -by- 0.70 m east west.
